            <description pref="true" source="British Museum">
                <text>This type of mask was worn by the Oba, on the hip, during important ceremonies. The mask is said to represent Idia, mother of Oba Esigie who ruled in the sixteenth century. The top of the hip mask is decorated with heads representing the Portuguese, symbolizing Benin's alliance with and control over Europeans. The Portuguese continued to appear in Benin art long after they had disappeared from Benin itself.
                    
                    P. Girshick Ben-Amos, The art of Benin (London, The British Museum Press, 1995)</text>
                <author>
